blocks.name: bdayimaon
blocks.content: Lemma for full-eta properties. The successor of the union of the image of the birthday function under a set is an ordinal. (Contributed by Scott Fenton, 20-Aug-2011.)
blocks.origin:
thm bdayimaon(class c0, class c1) {
  |- wi(wcel(c0, c1), wcel(csuc(cuni(cima(cbday, c0))), con0))
} = {
  sylib(wcel(c0, c1), wcel(csuc(cuni(cima(cbday, c0))), con0), wa(word(cuni(cima(cbday, c0))), wcel(cuni(cima(cbday, c0)), universe)))
  jctil(wcel(c0, c1), word(cuni(cima(cbday, c0))), wcel(cuni(cima(cbday, c0)), universe))
  syl(wcel(c0, c1), wcel(cuni(cima(cbday, c0)), universe), wcel(cima(cbday, c0), universe))
  mpan(wcel(c0, c1), wcel(cima(cbday, c0), universe), wfun(cbday))
  ax-mp(wfun(cbday), wfo(cbday, csur, con0))
  fofun(cbday, csur, con0)
  funimaexg(cbday, c0, c1)
  uniexg(cima(cbday, c0), universe)
  ax-mp(word(cuni(cima(cbday, c0))), wss(cima(cbday, c0), con0))
  sseqtri(cima(cbday, c0), con0, crn(cbday))
  imassrn(cbday, c0)
  ax-mp(wceq(crn(cbday), con0), wfo(cbday, csur, con0))
  bdayfo()
  forn(cbday, csur, con0)
  ssorduni(cima(cbday, c0))
  bitr3i(wa(word(cuni(cima(cbday, c0))), wcel(cuni(cima(cbday, c0)), universe)), wcel(csuc(cuni(cima(cbday, c0))), con0), wcel(cuni(cima(cbday, c0)), con0))
  elon2(cuni(cima(cbday, c0)))
  sucelon(cuni(cima(cbday, c0)))
}

  sylan2(wa(wcel(c0, csur), wcel(c1, csur)), w3a(wss(cdm(c0), c2), wss(cdm(c1), c2), wral(s0, c2, wn(wbr(cres(c1, csuc(cv(s0))), cslt, cres(c0, csuc(cv(s0))))))), wn(wbr(c1, cslt, c0)), wral(s0, cun(cdm(c0), cdm(c1)), wn(wbr(cres(c1, csuc(cv(s0))), cslt, cres(c0, csuc(cv(s0)))))))

blocks.name: nosupno
blocks.content: The next several theorems deal with a surreal "supremum". This surreal will ultimately be shown to bound ` A ` below and bound the restriction of any surreal above. We begin by showing that the given expression actually defines a surreal number. (Contributed by Scott Fenton, 5-Dec-2021.)

blocks.name: nosupbnd2lem1
blocks.content: Bounding law from above when a set of surreals has a maximum. (Contributed by Scott Fenton, 6-Dec-2021.)
blocks.origin:
thm nosupbnd2lem1(setvar s0, setvar s1, class c0, class c1, class c2) {
  |- wi(w3a(wa(wcel(c0, c1), wral(s0, c1, wn(wbr(c0, cslt, cv(s0))))), w3a(wss(c1, csur), wcel(c1, universe), wcel(c2, csur)), wral(s1, c1, wbr(cv(s1), cslt, c2))), wn(wbr(cres(c2, csuc(cdm(c0))), cslt, cun(c0, csn(cop(cdm(c0), c2o))))))
  -| diffsc(s1, c0)
  -| diffsc(s1, c1)
  -| diffsc(s1, c2)
} = {
  mpdan(w3a(wa(wcel(c0, c1), wral(s0, c1, wn(wbr(c0, cslt, cv(s0))))), w3a(wss(c1, csur), wcel(c1, universe), wcel(c2, csur)), wral(s1, c1, wbr(cv(s1), cslt, c2))), wn(wbr(cres(c2, csuc(cdm(c0))), cslt, cun(c0, csn(cop(cdm(c0), c2o))))), wbr(c0, cslt, c2))

blocks.name: noeta
blocks.content: The full-eta axiom for the surreal numbers. This is the single most important property of the surreals. It says that, given two sets of surreals such that one comes completely before the other, there is a surreal lying strictly between the two. Furthermore, there is an upper bound on the birthday of that surreal. Alling's axiom FE. (Contributed by Scott Fenton, 7-Dec-2021.)
